<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="192" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1841,2012]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,153,251]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="192" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1986,2012]" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Thomson" authorityName="Thomson" box="[584,898,1985,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Stirellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="191" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis box="[584,786,1985,2011]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="191">Stirellus convexus</emphasis>
Thomson
</taxonomicName>
but differs in having the male pygofer side with macrosetae dorsally, in the style shape and in having the aedeagal shaft with a slight dorsal expansion. This species is also close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Duan, Webb &amp; Zhang" authorityName="Duan, Webb &amp; Zhang" authorityYear="2016" box="[324,846,189,215]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Stirellus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multipunctatus">
<emphasis box="[324,590,189,215]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="192">Stirellus multipunctatus</emphasis>
Duan, Webb &amp; Zhang
</taxonomicName>
but can be easily distinguished by the orange-red or brownish red stripes on the head interrupted medially, and by the pygofer and aedeagus shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
